text.Taxonomy and naming:
Eremophila maculata was given its present name in 1859 by Ferdinand von Mueller in "Report on the Plants Collected During Mr. Babbage's Expedition into the North West Interior of South Australia in 1858". It was first formally described in 1822 by John Bellenden Ker Gawler as Stenochilus maculatus Ker Gawl.The specific epithet is from the Latin word maculata meaning "spotted", referring to the prominently spotted flowers.Three subspecies have been recognised by the Australian Plant Census:

Eremophila maculata subsp. brevifolia  (Benth.) Chinnock  which has leaves that are egg-shaped to almost circular and more than 2 mm (0.08 in) wide;
Eremophila maculata subsp. filifolia  Chinnock  which has leaves that are less than 2 mm (0.08 in) wide;
Eremophila maculata  (Ker Gawl.) F.Muell.  subsp. maculata which has leaves that are linear to lance-shaped and more than 2 mm (0.08 in) wide.The epithet brevifolia is from Latin and refers to the short leaves, and filifolia is Latin and refers to the long, narrow leaves.
